05354nam a22008055i 9781503610750DE-B159720210526051534.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210526t20202019cau    fo  d z      eng d  a2019004981  a97815036107507 a10.1515/97815036107502doi  a(DE-B1597)563728  a(OCoLC)1178769026  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA00aUA668b.I49 2019 4aUA668b.I49 2019 7aHIS0170002bisacsh04a355.309542231 aImy, Kate, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aFaithful Fighters :bIdentity and Power in the British Indian Army /cKate Imy. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2020] 4c©2019  a1 online resource (328 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aSouth Asia in Motion00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tList of Abbreviations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. Spiritual Swords and Martial Violence -- t2. Borders, Boundaries, and Belonging -- t3. Purifying the Soldier -- t4. The Government’s Salt from Fast to Famine -- t5. A Nation at Odds with Nationalism -- t6. Martial Masculinity in the Fascist Utopia -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tSelect Bibliography -- tIndex -- tALSO PUBLISHED IN THE SOUTH ASIA IN MOTION SERIES0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDuring the first four decades of the twentieth century, the British Indian Army possessed an illusion of racial and religious inclusivity. The army recruited diverse soldiers, known as the "Martial Races," including British Christians, Hindustani Muslims, Punjabi Sikhs, Hindu Rajputs, Pathans from northwestern India, and "Gurkhas" from Nepal. As anti-colonial activism intensified, military officials incorporated some soldiers' religious traditions into the army to keep them disciplined and loyal. They facilitated acts such as the fast of Ramadan for Muslim soldiers and allowed religious swords among Sikhs to recruit men from communities where anti-colonial sentiment grew stronger. Consequently, Indian nationalists and anti-colonial activists charged the army with fomenting racial and religious divisions. In Faithful Fighters, Kate Imy explores how military culture created unintended dialogues between soldiers and civilians, including Hindu nationalists, Sikh revivalists, and pan-Islamic activists. By the 1920s and '30s, the army constructed military schools and academies to isolate soldiers from anti-colonial activism. While this carefully managed military segregation crumbled under the pressure of the Second World War, Imy argues that the army militarized racial and religious difference, creating lasting legacies for the violent partition and independence of India, and the endemic warfare and violence of the post-colonial world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aIdentification (Religion)xHistoryy20th century. 0aNationalismzIndiaxHistoryy20th century. 0aReligion and statezIndiaxHistoryy20th century. 0aSoldierszIndiaxSocial conditionsy20th century. 7aHISTORY / Asia / India & South Asia.2bisacsh  aBritish Empire.  aBritish Indian Army.  aFirst World War.  aIndian nationalism.  aanti-colonialism.  acolonial armies.  afascism.  ahistory of religion.  amartial races.  awar and society.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Contemporary Collection eBook Packagez978311064982608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2020 Englishz978311070473008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2020z9783110704525oZDB-23-DEG08iTitle is part of